<subSubSection pageId="110" pageNumber="111" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="110.[189,457,1835,1861]" box="[189,457,1835,1861]" pageId="110" pageNumber="111">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,457,1835,1861]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="110" pageNumber="111" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,457,1835,1861]" pageId="110" pageNumber="111">Differential diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="110.[189,1399,1884,2025]" pageId="110" pageNumber="111">
Very different from all other 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Meigen" authorityYear="1822" box="[532,641,1884,1910]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Sphegina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="110" pageNumber="111" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[532,641,1884,1910]" italics="true" pageId="110" pageNumber="111">Sphegina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and easily distinguished by the characters given in the key. The spoon-shaped lobe posteriorly on male sternum IV (without expanded apical part in other species) and the deeply bilobed surstylus, with the ventral lobe on the right side as long as the dorsal one (much shorter) are easily observed and unique characters.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
